segments.text: Question about the other benefits besides pay.
I mean, you said just a minute ago that you weren't interested in pay when you were... Well, that wasn't your main objective.
I don't think that up until 1963 you're really interested in what the job was to be done.
And I had so many fantastic
jobs by, I was just enthusiastic about the Air Force.
And getting back to Massawa, after I shipped all these people home, the re-enlistment rate at Massawa jumped to about three percent.
I mean, three times.
Really?
Oh yeah, because
Even though you were kind of a hard nose, did it sound like?
Oh, yeah.
Because they figured they had a mission.
And they were interested.
And of course, we're getting off of pay, but...
Another thing we set up was an educational program at the University of Maryland I think came in and set up schools there.
And you encourage all these young men instead of going down to the beer garden why they go to school at night.
And they could get the first two years of college out of the way by going to night school at Masato.
and you could raise their work schedule so that they could always attend school.
So you're greatly involved in doing a good job and knowing you're doing a good job and so you're really not interested in and you were getting pretty well paid.
See when I got promoted to full colonel
By 1942 you had nine years service and you were full colonel until 57.
Your pay was pretty good all during those years anyway.
The only thing I say is today where there is more emphasis on pay and benefits that
there were a lot more people talking about it.
And therefore, more people are setting the standard that you have to pay the military more than they're now being paid.
And well, when the Department of Labor, I think it's the Department of Labor, establishes
that you have to make $9,600 to be above the poverty level, and you have a third of your military making less than that, why then everybody in the military thinks they're in the poverty level.
But that doesn't of course take into account the other benefits
Well, you have... You do have a considerable amount of benefits in the armed forces where you don't get those in business.
Often you don't have those in business.
Well... Let's go back to this one again.
What I'd like to do is, when did you start thinking about this differential in pay and when did you start thinking that it was becoming a problem?
have not been able to keep your best young commanders in.
Well, it wasn't a problem while I was in the service.
In fact, it wasn't a problem that you really get to looking at it until you get into the building business and you get to realize how much some people are making.
I see, yeah, right, yeah.
See, you really haven't...
you really don't know.
You look at somebody and you don't know if he's making $60,000 or $80,000 or whether or not he's making $18,000.
You don't know that.
When you get into a position where you get to know how much various people are making in the various occupations, why you just get to the point that
that the commanders and managers in the military are just way underpaid.

realize this during the 1950s when the Air Force was expanding did you know people who were colonels and generals who were getting out of the service instead of staying in 30 years they were getting out early they were getting out after 20 years because they could get a better paying job?
No I don't really remember of any particular instance where
individuals were getting out.
Sometimes a general officer would get an offer of a good civilian job and he would retire twenty-seven year service or something of this sort.
But see the twenty year retirement, I don't remember when it exactly came in, but it hasn't been in very much before I retired.
But I would say that you're... See, when I went and got in the Air Force, you had all kinds of jobs.
And now, you get into specifics where you have an individual who does nothing but fly.
Now, maybe he flies every third day.
And he has two days, maybe one day, that he has to brush up on his missions.
And he has another day of doing nothing.
I mean, this is whereas we don't use this talent in part-time jobs.
What do you mean by that?
I don't think I understand.
Well, OK. My son-in-law was a navigator.
And he was stationed in Hawaii when we were there.
And that's where he met my wife.
oldest daughter, and he was a navigator.
And he maybe flew a mission once every two days, or three days, I mean every three or four days.
While he was on the ground, he didn't have anything to do because he was on call for a mission.
Well, he could spend so much time taking University of Maryland courses, college courses,
But what do you do the rest of the time?

And we don't spend enough time of developing part-time jobs so that he could be a supply officer or something else that would be productive for him during his off time, during his eight hour a day work day.
OK, that brings me to another question.
You said that when you were the commander of the 39th Air Division, here you are up in northern Japan.
And you're snowed in pretty much of the winter.
And it's probably fairly cold and miserable up there.
You had things set up for the men and officers, such as the University of Maryland night courses.
What other type of entertainment or after duty
programs did you have or did you try to develop any of these programs so these people would have something to do?
Well, you develop bowling alleys.
Did you build some bowling alleys?
Well, we may have had them there.
We had quite an extensive
special service programs, a bowling alley.
Then you had your basketball, both your high school basketball and your base basketball teams, and that you had visiting teams come in or visiting high school teams come in.
And you had an extensive youth program of teaching the
high school kids of how to shoot a rifle, for example.
And we gave them dancing lessons and ceramic lessons.
And my oldest daughter took painting lessons from a professional Japanese painter in oils.
And so you set up a lot of...
swimming, indoor swimming pool, and you teach everybody how to swim.
So you had a really extensive youth program to keep out of trouble.
But to get everybody involved in some kind of activity is most difficult.
Because some of them just don't want to do anything.
Any directed activity.
They want to do what they want to do.
And then you of course have an extensive library so that people who are readers can read.
What about liberty?
What kind of liberty sections did you have?
What do you mean liberty?
they worked basically in Japan they worked eight to four or eight to five days something like that and then how often would they have the duty to stay on all night on the base all night?
Oh not very much.
Normally you left that up to your squaring commanders where you like Christmas by you had required to keep say fifty percent of your
of his squadron on base and then you just depend on him to manage it.
You really didn't, then you had alert aircraft and that was on a roster basis.
So the officers and men then got plenty of time off?
Yeah, they'd get plenty of time off.
Not in Japan, up in Misawa, unless you go down to Tokyo.
You didn't have a lot of off-base activities.
Okay, now let's go to your next duty assignment.
You said you got your next duty assignment because you did a good job up in Missawa.
Basically, what did you do as the Deputy for Plans and Operations of Pacific Air Force Hawaii?
Well, that...
involved just about what I wrote out there.
Advising the commander.
Well, see the fifth of the PACAF headquarters was organized where you had a commander and you had a vice commander and then you had two deputies.
And then the entire staff were under those two deputies so that in your chain of command
You had operations, flying safety, anything that had to do with the flying program, and anything to do with the plans program.
Those were under your direction.
And then you had underneath you, then you had a director of plans and you had a director of operations.
And then you dealt through them as far as the staff is concerned.
Who was it?
How about cutting that off now?
So basically, then, we have four generals who are running the Fifth Air Force.
Well, you're also your- Is that the chain of command?
Well, also you had-
My deputy for operations was also a brigadier general.
Oh, I see.
So you were a senior brigadier, and he was a junior.
Yeah.
And then your director of plans was also a, if the slot was a brigadier general.
At the time, he wasn't a brigadier.
He was a colonel.
But normally, he was occupying a BG slot.
And see, I was occupying a major general slot.
Then the commander was a four star and the vice commander was a three star.
And then you had two two stars.
And then under this other side, under logistics, while you had the surgeon was a brigadier general, he had a number of brigadier generals underneath him.
Who was, at this time, who was your general?
Well, General O'Donnell, Rosie O'Donnell, was the commander.
He was a four star?
He was a four star.
And then you had General Moorman, who was a classmate of mine from West Point, was a three star.
And then I was underneath any of them.
Why weren't you promoted to a two-star then?
Well, see this was getting down to the point, and this is rationalizing I would say, that you were getting down to the point where you had twenty-eight year service.
At that time I had twenty-eight year service.
And the Air Force promotes their individuals rather early.
And according to just rumors that I'd been told by another classmate that at that stage the Air Force just wasn't promoting anybody to a higher grade.
because that would, you'd just get more retired pay and things of this sort.
Anyway, why, I didn't really think about retiring at all, because when I was brought into PACF headquarters, why, General O'Donnell was positive that he could get me promoted.
That's what he told you?
Yeah, and so that,
I didn't prepare for retirement.
As far as I was concerned, as long as I was on active duty, I didn't prepare myself at all for any retirement job and for retirement life because I was too busy doing a military job.
And these are both of the
The director of the deputy for operations and plans is an extremely responsible guy.
It's a staff job, as you understand it.
You prepare operational orders and send them out for execution, the 5th Air Force.
And the 5th Air Force in turn sends it down to the air divisions.
And you prepare all kinds of plans for various types of emergencies.
and you go out and inspect probably twice a year.
All the different bases?
All the different bases.
And how can you differentiate between your job as the deputy for plans and operations and then your next job in 1962 and 63 as the deputy for administration and logistics?
In other words, you were switching from one of the deputies to another deputy.
Well, the reason for that is the operations and plans job is probably the most important one.
In view of the fact that I wasn't going to get promoted by General O'Donnell had made available to him a
a major general that he particularly wanted.
So I had the choice of either I could retire at that time or I could move over and take this other plans and logistics job for the remaining one year I had before retiring.
When you learned that you weren't going to be promoted, what were your feelings?
Well, your ego gets pretty well tarnished.
I didn't go into the darks of depression or anything.
I enjoyed my job over in administration logistics.
It was a real high-powered job.
more the business side of running a Far East PACAF headquarters, Pacific Air Forces, than the plans and operations.
Because all of your justification before the air staff in Washington on how much money you needed to run the PACAF command,
had to be justified.
You had to prepare all kinds of documents that way.
The personnel that you got followed through your director of personnel.
So it's really, on that side, it's more of the business side of running a big corporation than the plans and operations.
That would prepare you then for civilian duties.
Yeah, you would think so.
And did you think about that?
No, you really don't.
As far as I was concerned, I really didn't think about retiring until about three months before retiring and decide what you're going to do.
And you really have no, you don't know what you're going to do.
I mean, you never thought about it, what you're going to do.
And you have a lot of major problems in retiring.
at age 55 with I guess your ego that you're pretty good.
And so you say, well what am I going to do?
You have a job here of dividing up say $200 million in 1963 among various bases and activities and what have you.
And you have all kinds of funds.
You have 750 staff personnel.
And you're taking care of about 100,000 people at 20 air bases.
So that's a big job.
And then you retire.
And you say, well, boy, I should be able to run General Dynamics.
And so you start looking for a job, and that's a completely different story, I'm sure.
We're going to talk about your retirement in a bit.
It's rather interesting to me that here you are at a top staff position, 1963.
Vietnam is just starting to wind up.
Kennedy is ascending.
15,000 advisors into Vietnam in 1963.
We hadn't started the bombing yet.
That didn't come until 1965.
But the Air Force, and especially the Fifth Air Force, must have.
Were you at all involved with any of the early?
Can you tell me about that, your experience, your involvement in Vietnam?
No, I was in Vietnam and had gone all over Vietnam.
Well, I don't know whether it'ssomewhere in between 61 and 63.
I mean it was while I was in one of those jobs.
And of course we had some activity.

establishing training programs for the Vietnamese pilots and discussion of technical schools, whether or not you bring them back to the United States and train your mechanics and radio operators and all the other people.
I would say the big decision that

which was a controversy, is whether or not you teach, you write the training manuals in Vietnamese and let them learn in their native language or whether or not you bring all these people back to the States and teach them English first and then let them learn from the books written in English.
in the headquarters there why there were two proposals.
One of them is, as far as I was concerned, we should establish a technical school in Vietnam and write the books in Vietnamese.
That was your opinion?
That was my opinion.
It seemed to me it would have been a lot easier to do it that way and not have
these people coming back, flowing back to the states in vast numbers and taking so much longer time to be trained.
But the way that the Air Force was doing it worldwide was bringing the indigenous personnel back to the states, teach them English, and then let them go through our technical schools.
That's the way it was going to run.
And did you put in a proposal to set up a technical school?
That was in the headquarters, and I don't think it ever got beyond the headquarters.
That would have been, just an aside here, that would have been an excellent job for you.
Well, I had a good job.
No, seriously though, because you had had so much experience in setting up schools.
Did you ever think of that?
No, I never did.
Well, the thing about it, by that time, and not getting promoted, I knew I was going to retire.
So it just wasn't worth the while to get involved in a technical training school or command or what have you at that time.
Do you remember any high-level discussions besides this issue?
Do you remember any other high-level discussions about Vietnam at Fifth Air Force Headquarters?
You mean at PACAF Headquarters?
Yeah.
Well, I attended most of the meetings thatlet's see, you have Pacific Air Forces and you have Pacific PACOM, which is Pacific Command.
Now that was at the time
was run by a Navy four-star admiral.
And of course that was an integrated command, had Army, Air Force, Marines, Navy running it.
And the generals in Vietnam reported to him.
The generals in Vietnam reported to him.
So did you sit in at some of those meetings?
Oh yeah, well I was...
I was involved in most of the plans in Vietnam, and of course I think it's known that we the politicians just controlled Vietnam War to the extent that it was a no-win situation.
And was that the basic feeling?
Now think back 1961 through 1963.
I know that I'm sure that you feel that way today, but is that what you felt back then?
That the politicians were controlling you too much?
Well you had two situations.
One of them is you had the Army trying to control the jungle warfare.
They wanted their primary mission to be jungle warfare.
And of course you had the Air Force having most of the airplanes and the pilots.
and you had the Army still trying to get back their close support airplanes.
They figured that they could do a better job than the Air Force was doing.
So they had some inner service right there.
Yeah, but most of your proposals were expansion, and of course it did expand, but it still
didn't expand as much as the Air Force would have liked to at the time because if you go over and visit Vietnam it was so primitive.
I mean you go back in the backwoods and the natives were still throwing spears.
I mean they were armed with spears.
and bows and arrows type of thing.
And these mountaineers, I mean they were tough cookies, but they just didn't have the armament, the guns and what have you, and probably were pretty close to untrainable.
The guns that we provided them,
whatever the MPO rifle or whatever the type of rifle that we provided them, the stock was just too long for them to get it up under, get it up to the shoulder.
I mean they were small people.
And so they had to hold it like I did when I was 12 years old.
Dad's 12 gauge, 10 gauge shotgun.
You hold it under your underarm and you try to shoot it.
And they were very, very primitive people.
You just can't imagine how primitive a major part of the Vietnamese people were.
If we couldn't lick them with all our modern tanks and what have you, we'd better quit.
just build it up so gradually that you really go in in a no-win situation.
And I think we, at the time, we were voicing the same opinion.
And I think the military, during that period of time, were trying to expand the war to win the war.
Now, specifically, why were you sent to Vietnam?
What was your mission?
Well, I went over there on a staff visit to visit all of the air bases that were in existence for use by our own Air Force and also the Vietnamese Air Force.
How many air bases did we have in 1962?
We had, I think we had two that were finished and we were building about two others or three others.
And then of course I met General LeMay over there when he came over there for a visit and somewhere in my files I have a report that I read and wrote after his visit.
He came, he flew in, he was chief of staff at the airports at the time and he came in to look over
And he flew around.
